# Rust Documentation Rule

When writing or editing Rust doc comments and module docs, follow these rules. They align with the [Microsoft Pragmatic Rust Guidelines - Documentation](https://microsoft.github.io/rust-guidelines/guidelines/docs/) (M-FIRST-DOC-SENTENCE, M-MODULE-DOCS, M-CANONICAL-DOCS, M-DOC-INLINE).

## First sentence (summary)

- The **first sentence** of an item's doc comment is the summary shown in the module overview.
- Keep the first sentence on **one line** and to approximately **15 words** so docs stay skimmable and avoid widows in rendered output.
- Use outer doc comments (`///`) for items; use inner (`//!`) only for module- or crate-level docs.

## Module documentation

- **Public modules** must have `//!` module documentation.
- The first sentence of the module doc must follow the same rule (one line, ~15 words).
- Module docs should cover, where relevant:
  - What the module contains and when to use it (and when not)
  - Examples and subsystem specs (e.g. formatting language)
  - Observable side effects and guarantees
  - Relevant implementation details (e.g. system APIs used)

## Canonical sections

- The **summary sentence** must always be present.
- Use these **canonical sections** when they apply (after the summary and any extended prose):
  - `# Examples` - one or more usage examples
  - `# Errors` - if the item returns `Result`, describe known error conditions
  - `# Panics` - if the item can panic, describe when
  - `# Safety` - if the item is `unsafe` or can cause UB, list all conditions the caller must uphold
  - `# Abort` — if the item can abort the process, describe when
  - `# Implementation note` — optional; use when implementation details (e.g. algorithm choice, borrow tricks) help future readers
- **Do not** use parameter tables. Describe parameters in prose (e.g. "Copies from `src` to `dst`"), not as a `# Parameters` list.

## Documentation for private items

Document non-trivial private items; lean **yes** rather than no.

### When to document private `fn`s

Add `///` doc comments for private functions when **any** of these apply:

- Body > ~12–15 meaningful lines (not counting braces/empty lines)
- Contains `unsafe` block — always document (even one line), and include `/// # Safety`
- Enforces module-level invariants the rest of the module relies on
- Name is not 100% self-explanatory (common in builders, parsers, state machines, internal helpers with lifetime trickery)
- Involves subtle performance choices, borrow splitting, pinning, etc.
- Will likely be read during debugging or future refactoring

### When to skip

**Do not** force doc comments on tiny obvious helpers: < 8–10 LOC, name clearly describes what it does, no safety/performance subtlety.

### Style for private items

- Write **full sentences** starting with a verb in third person (same style as public API).
- Focus first on **purpose** ("why does this exist?"), then important **semantics**, preconditions, postconditions, or safety notes.
- Prefer brevity over redundancy — aim for 1–4 lines unless complexity demands more.
- Use markdown sections when helpful: `# Panics`, `# Safety`, `# Implementation note`, etc.

Examples of good private doc comments:

```rust
/// Computes the smallest power of two ≥ n without overflowing usize.
///
/// Returns `None` on overflow (very large n).
fn next_power_of_two(n: usize) -> Option<usize> { … }

/// # Safety
///
/// Caller must guarantee `index < self.len()`.
/// This is **not** checked.
unsafe fn get_unchecked_mut(&mut self, index: usize) -> &mut T { … }

/// Splits mutable borrow into two disjoint parts without reborrowing the whole struct.
/// Avoids temporary lifetime issues that prevent later split borrows.
///
/// See rust-lang/rust#XXXXX for related borrow checker limitation.
fn split_two_disjoint_mut(&mut self, a: usize, b: usize) -> (&mut T, &mut T) { … }
```

### When editing or refactoring

- If adding complexity to an existing private `fn` — add or improve the doc comment.
- If simplifying a heavily documented private `fn` — keep or shorten the comment; do not delete useful invariants.
- Never remove `/// # Safety` or `/// # Panics` sections unless you are certain the condition is no longer relevant.

### Quick decision checklist

- Is the function trivial / name self-documenting? — usually no doc
- `unsafe`? — mandatory short `/// # Safety`
- 12–15 LOC or subtle logic? — yes, purpose-first doc
- Important for module coherence? — document invariants / why

Follow this balance: avoid doc noise on tiny helpers, but prevent "tribal knowledge" in medium-to-large modules.

## Re-exports

- When publicly re-exporting **crate items** with `pub use foo::Foo` (or `pub use foo::*`), add **`#[doc(inline)]`** at the use site so the re-export is inlined in the docs.
- **Do not** use `#[doc(inline)]` for `std` or third-party types; leave those as opaque re-exports so it is clear they are external.
- Prefer explicit re-exports over globs; `#[doc(inline)]` does not override the general preference to avoid glob re-exports.

## Reference

- **Source**: [Documentation - Pragmatic Rust Guidelines](https://microsoft.github.io/rust-guidelines/guidelines/docs/)

Apply these documentation rules for all Rust doc comments and `//!` module docs unless the user explicitly asks to ignore them.
